{{Orphan|date=July 2018}} [[File: Atul Gupta.jpg|thumb]] '''Atul Gupta''' (born 14 June 1968)<ref name="kc">{{cite news|last1=Cowan|first1=Kyle|title=Gigaba says Atul Gupta ‘is not SA citizen’ – but we have proof that he is|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2018-03-06-gigaba-says-atul-gupta-is-not-sa-citizen--but-we-have-proof-that-he-is/|accessdate=20 March 2018|work=South Africa|agency=TimesLive|date=6 March 2018}}</ref> is a South African businessman and a member of the [[Gupta family]], well-known in the country for their business dealings. He started the family's first business in South Africa, Sahara Computers, in 1993.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/how-the-guptas-of-saharanpur-came-to-be-known-as-the-zuptas-of-south-africa/articleshow/60101573.cms|title=How the Guptas of Saharanpur came to be known as the Zuptas of South Africa|last=Gupta|first=Atul|date=20 August 2017|work=Economic Times|access-date=14 June 2018}}</ref> Today, the Gupta family<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-22513410|title=The Guptas and their links to South Africa's Jacob Zuma|last=Gupta|first=Atul|date=14 February 2018|work=BBC|access-date= 14 June 2018}}</ref>'s businesses in South Africa include coal mines, computers, newspapers and a news channel.
== Career == Atul started the family's first business in [[South Africa]], [[Sahara Computers]], in 1993. Today, the [[Gupta family]]'s businesses in South Africa include [[Coal mining|coal mines]], [[computer]]s, newspapers and a news channel. Bongi Ngema-Zuma, one of former President Jacob Zuma's wives, worked for the Gupta-controlled JIC Mining Services. Duduzile Zuma, his daughter, was a director at Sahara Computers. His son, Duduzane Zuma, was a director of a few Gupta-owned companies but stepped down last year after public furore.
