'''Isabel H. Benham''' (August 4, 1909 – May 18, 2013) was an American railroad finance expert. She was the first female partner at any [[Wall Street]] bond house.<ref>{{cite news|author=Laurence Arnold|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/isabel-benham-dies-railroad-expert-first-female-partner-at-a-wall-street-bond-house/2013/06/12/6e604ade-d387-11e2-b05f-3ea3f0e7bb5a_story.html|title=Isabel Benham dies; railroad expert first female partner at a Wall Street bond house|publisher=The Washington Post|date=June 12, 2013|accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.railwayage.com/index.php/management/obituary-isabel-h-benham-103.html|title=Obituary: Isabel H. Benham, 103|magazine=Railway Age|date=June 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/01/13/magazine/turning-a-railroad-around.html|first=Winston|last=Williams|date=January 13, 1985|title=Turning a Railroad Around|newspaper=The New York Times|quote=''It's all very strange and unbelievable to me,'' says Isabel H. Benham, president of Printon, Kane Research, a transportation consulting firm in New York. ''It's a three-ring circus.''|accessdate=June 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name="bloomberg-2013-06-11">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-06-11/isabel-benham-woman-who-blazed-path-on-wall-street-dies-at-103.html|title=Isabel Benham, Woman Who Blazed Path on Wall Street, Dies at 103|last=Arnold|first=Laurence|date=June 11, 2013|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=June 17, 2013}}</ref> She was a graduate of [[Bryn Mawr College]].
