{{about|the Cincinnati-based business family|other people named Lindner|Lindner (disambiguation)}} {{refimprove|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox family | name = Lindner family | caste = | crest = | crestcaption = | image = | imagecaption = | birth_place = | region = | early_forms = | origin = [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]] | members = {{plainlist| * [[Carl Lindner Jr.]] * [[Carl Lindner III]] }} | connectedmembers= | otherfamilies = | distinctions = {{plainlist| * Insurance business * Sports team ownership }} | traditions = | heirlooms = | estate = | meaning = | footnotes = }} The '''Lindner family''' is a family that has been prominent in the [[Cincinnati metropolitan area]] since the mid-20th century. They are known for their work in the insurance and investments business. As of 2015, ''[[Forbes]]'' ranks them as the 129th richest family in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/lindner/|title=Lindner family|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=November 21, 2016}}</ref> They are also known for their involvement in professional sports; [[Carl Lindner Jr.|Carl Jr.]] was a part owner and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of the [[Cincinnati Reds]], [[Carl Lindner III|Carl III]] is the majority owner and CEO of [[FC Cincinnati]], and the family's contributions to the [[Western & Southern Open]] led to its venue being titled the [[Lindner Family Tennis Center]].
== History == The Lindner family's rise to prominence began with Carl Lindner Sr. opening a dairy processing plant in [[Norwood, Ohio|Norwood]], Ohio in 1940. The business, [[United Dairy Farmers]], had expanded to thirty stores by 1960, and the family bought the [[American Financial Group]] with their savings. By the mid-1960s, Carl Sr.'s sons were running the family's businesses: [[Carl Lindner Jr.|Carl Jr.]] was running American Financial Group and Richard was running United Dairy Farmers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnatimagazine.com/citywiseblog/lindner-milk-money-fortune-500/|title=The Lindner Family: From Milk Money to The Fortune 500|last=Murtha|first=Lisa|date=October 30, 2014|work=[[Cincinnati (magazine)|Cincinnati]]|accessdate=November 21, 2016}}</ref>
In 1989, the Lindner family founded and funded the [[Cincinnati Hills Christian Academy]].
In 1999, Carl Jr. bought controlling ownership in the [[Cincinnati Reds]], which he held until selling to [[Robert Castellini]] in 2005.
In 2015, [[Carl Lindner III|Carl III]] became majority owner and chief executive owner of the newly formed soccer club [[FC Cincinnati (2016–18)|FC Cincinnati]].
